When a parent raises a concern about a teacher repeatedly humiliating and picking on their child, the school's complaints procedure will be followed [1.10]. This type of concern, described as "unfairly singling out a pupil or attempting to humiliate them, bullying or belittling a pupil," is considered "poor practice" that initially does not reach the threshold for child protection action [1.10].

The complaints are managed by the head teacher or other members of the senior leadership team [1.10]. All complaints will be dealt with within 28 days [1.10]. If the complaint escalates into a child protection concern, it will automatically be managed under the school's child protection procedures [1.10].

