When a student actively discloses abuse, the staff member engages in a direct conversation with the pupil. During this conversation, the staff member is instructed to allow the pupil to speak freely, remain calm, offer reassuring words, and avoid asking investigative questions (though clarifying questions for referral are acceptable). The staff member must inform the pupil that the information will be passed on and that someone will see them before the end of the day. The staff member then reports verbally to the Designated Safeguarding Lead (DSL) [1.13]. Parental notification is normally sought, but if it could increase risk to the child, advice is sought from Children's Social Care first [2].

When staff only suspect abuse based on signs, their responsibility is to report their concerns to the Designated Safeguarding Lead (DSL). Staff are explicitly told that it is not their responsibility to investigate or decide whether a child has been abused, and they should report all concerns, regardless of how minor they may seem [1.11.L21]. The document does not detail specific conversational protocols with the child at the point of suspicion, but rather emphasizes the reporting obligation to the DSL.

